#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:399
msgid "Passing a callable to custom markers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:403
msgid "Below is the config file that will be used in the next examples::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:405
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    for marker in item.iter_markers(name='my_marker'):\n"
"        print(marker)\n"
"        sys.stdout.flush()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:413
msgid ""
"A custom marker can have its argument set, i.e. ``args`` and ``kwargs`` "
"properties, defined by either invoking it as a callable or using ``pytest."
"mark.MARKER_NAME.with_args``. These two methods achieve the same effect most "
"of the time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:415
msgid ""
"However, if there is a callable as the single positional argument with no "
"keyword arguments, using the ``pytest.mark.MARKER_NAME(c)`` will not pass "
"``c`` as a positional argument but decorate ``c`` with the custom marker "
"(see :ref:`MarkDecorator <mark>`). Fortunately, ``pytest.mark.MARKER_NAME."
"with_args`` comes to the rescue::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:417
msgid ""
"# content of test_custom_marker.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"def hello_world(*args, **kwargs):\n"
"    return 'Hello World'\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.my_marker.with_args(hello_world)\n"
"def test_with_args():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:427
msgid "The output is as follows::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:429
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q -s\n"
"Mark(name='my_marker', args=(<function hello_world at 0xdeadbeef>,), "
"kwargs={})\n"
".\n"
"1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:434
msgid ""
"We can see that the custom marker has its argument set extended with the "
"function ``hello_world``. This is the key difference between creating a "
"custom marker as a callable, which invokes ``__call__`` behind the scenes, "
"and using ``with_args``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:438
msgid "Reading markers which were set from multiple places"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:444
msgid ""
"If you are heavily using markers in your test suite you may encounter the "
"case where a marker is applied several times to a test function.  From "
"plugin code you can read over all such settings.  Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:447
msgid ""
"# content of test_mark_three_times.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.glob(\"module\", x=1)\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.glob(\"class\", x=2)\n"
"class TestClass(object):\n"
"    @pytest.mark.glob(\"function\", x=3)\n"
"    def test_something(self):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:457
msgid ""
"Here we have the marker \"glob\" applied three times to the same test "
"function.  From a conftest file we can read it like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:460
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    for mark in item.iter_markers(name='glob'):\n"
"        print (\"glob args=%s kwargs=%s\" %(mark.args, mark.kwargs))\n"
"        sys.stdout.flush()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:468
msgid "Let's run this without capturing output and see what we get::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:470
msgid ""
"$ pytest -q -s\n"
"glob args=('function',) kwargs={'x': 3}\n"
"glob args=('class',) kwargs={'x': 2}\n"
"glob args=('module',) kwargs={'x': 1}\n"
".\n"
"1 passed in 0.12 seconds"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:478
msgid "marking platform specific tests with pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:482
msgid ""
"Consider you have a test suite which marks tests for particular platforms, "
"namely ``pytest.mark.darwin``, ``pytest.mark.win32`` etc. and you also have "
"tests that run on all platforms and have no specific marker.  If you now "
"want to have a way to only run the tests for your particular platform, you "
"could use the following plugin::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:488
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"#\n"
"import sys\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"ALL = set(\"darwin linux win32\".split())\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_runtest_setup(item):\n"
"    supported_platforms = ALL.intersection(mark.name for mark in item."
"iter_markers())\n"
"    plat = sys.platform\n"
"    if supported_platforms and plat not in supported_platforms:\n"
"        pytest.skip(\"cannot run on platform %s\" % (plat))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:501
msgid ""
"then tests will be skipped if they were specified for a different platform. "
"Let's do a little test file to show how this looks like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:504
msgid ""
"# content of test_plat.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.darwin\n"
"def test_if_apple_is_evil():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.linux\n"
"def test_if_linux_works():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.win32\n"
"def test_if_win32_crashes():\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"def test_runs_everywhere():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:523
msgid ""
"then you will see two tests skipped and two executed tests as expected::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:525
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rs # this option reports skip reasons\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items\n"
"\n"
"test_plat.py s.s.                                                    [100%]\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"SKIP [2] $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/conftest.py:12: cannot run on platform linux\n"
"\n"
"=================== 2 passed, 2 skipped in 0.12 seconds ===================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:537
msgid ""
"Note that if you specify a platform via the marker-command line option like "
"this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:539
msgid ""
"$ pytest -m linux\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items / 3 deselected\n"
"\n"
"test_plat.py .                                                       [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================== 1 passed, 3 deselected in 0.12 seconds =================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:549
msgid ""
"then the unmarked-tests will not be run.  It is thus a way to restrict the "
"run to the specific tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:552
msgid "Automatically adding markers based on test names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:556
msgid ""
"If you a test suite where test function names indicate a certain type of "
"test, you can implement a hook that automatically defines markers so that "
"you can use the ``-m`` option with it. Let's look at this test module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:561
msgid ""
"# content of test_module.py\n"
"\n"
"def test_interface_simple():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_interface_complex():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_event_simple():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"def test_something_else():\n"
"    assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:575
msgid ""
"We want to dynamically define two markers and can do it in a ``conftest.py`` "
"plugin::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:578
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"import pytest\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(items):\n"
"    for item in items:\n"
"        if \"interface\" in item.nodeid:\n"
"            item.add_marker(pytest.mark.interface)\n"
"        elif \"event\" in item.nodeid:\n"
"            item.add_marker(pytest.mark.event)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:588
msgid "We can now use the ``-m option`` to select one set::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:590
msgid ""
"$ pytest -m interface --tb=short\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items / 2 deselected\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py FF                                                    [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"__________________________ test_interface_simple "
"___________________________\n"
"test_module.py:3: in test_interface_simple\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"__________________________ test_interface_complex "
"__________________________\n"
"test_module.py:6: in test_interface_complex\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"================== 2 failed, 2 deselected in 0.12 seconds =================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:609
msgid "or to select both \"event\" and \"interface\" tests::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/example/markers.rst:611
msgid ""
"$ pytest -m \"interface or event\" --tb=short\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-3.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR, inifile:\n"
"collected 4 items / 1 deselected\n"
"\n"
"test_module.py FFF                                                   [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"__________________________ test_interface_simple "
"___________________________\n"
"test_module.py:3: in test_interface_simple\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"__________________________ test_interface_complex "
"__________________________\n"
"test_module.py:6: in test_interface_complex\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"____________________________ test_event_simple "
"_____________________________\n"
"test_module.py:9: in test_event_simple\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"E   assert 0\n"
"================== 3 failed, 1 deselected in 0.12 seconds =================="
msgstr ""
